04740nam a22006495i 9780804796774DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015030662  a97808047967747 a10.1515/97808047967742doi  a(DE-B1597)564400  a(OCoLC)1198930929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aJZ1480b.M564 2016 4aJZ1480b.M564 2016 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a327.730562231 aMintz, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Polythink Syndrome :bU.S. Foreign Policy Decisions on 9/11, Afghanistan, Iraq, Iran, Syria, and ISIS /cCarly Wayne, Alex Mintz. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Polythink Syndrome -- t2. Symptoms, Causes, and Consequences of Polythink -- t3. The 9/11 Attacks: Polythink in National Security -- t4. Polythink and Afghanistan War Decisions: War Initiation and Termination -- t5. Decision Making in the Iraq War: From Groupthink to Polythink -- t6. Polythink in the Iranian Nuclear Dispute: Decisions of the U.S. and Israel -- t7. Recent Challenges: The Syria Debate, the Israeli- Palestinian Peace Negotiations, and the ISIS Decision -- t8. The Global Nature of Polythink and Its Productive Potential -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy do presidents and their advisors often make sub-optimal decisions on military intervention, escalation, de-escalation, and termination of conflicts? The leading concept of group dynamics, groupthink, offers one explanation: policy-making groups make sub-optimal decisions due to their desire for conformity and uniformity over dissent, leading to a failure to consider other relevant possibilities. But presidential advisory groups are often fragmented and divisive. This book therefore scrutinizes polythink, a group decision-making dynamic whereby different members in a decision-making unit espouse a plurality of opinions and divergent policy prescriptions, resulting in a disjointed decision-making process or even decision paralysis. The book analyzes eleven national security decisions, including the national security policy designed prior to the terrorist attacks of 9/11, the decisions to enter into and withdraw from Afghanistan and Iraq, the 2007 "surge" decision, the crisis over the Iranian nuclear program, the UN Security Council decision on the Syrian Civil War, the faltering Kerry Peace Process in the Middle East, and the U.S. decision on military operations against ISIS. Based on the analysis of these case studies, the authors address implications of the polythink phenomenon, including prescriptions for avoiding and/or overcoming it, and develop strategies and tools for what they call Productive Polythink. The authors also show the applicability of polythink to business, industry, and everyday decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aGroup decision makingzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aNational securityzUnited StatesxDecision makingvCase studies. 4aBureaucratic Politics. 4aCognitive Bias. 4aConflict. 4aForeign Policy Decision Making. 4aGroup Decision Making. 4aGroupthink. 4aMiddle East. 4aPolitical Psychology. 4aPolythink. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aWayne, Carly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479677440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/c